ear handling, incorrect last-day detection) can be caught entirely with parametrized unit tests using various reference times.","test_description":"Parametrized unit tests with fixed reference times and diverse cron expressions: standard minute/hour/day patterns, edge cases (last-day-of-month for February in leap/non-leap years, nearest-weekday patterns), and boundary moments (midnight transitions, end-of-day). Verify computed next-run timestamps are correct and consistent with timezone representation.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The overlap detector identifies when two schedules would fire within the configured minimum gap (e.g., 5 minutes) and reports the conflicting time windows.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Overlap detection is pure range/interval logic: given two schedule objects with computed run times, determine if they overlap or collide within a gap threshold. No I/O, no external state, no non-determinism. Real failures (boundary condition bugs like off-by-one at exactly-the-gap-time, false positives, false negatives) can all be caught by unit tests comparing schedule pairs. No need to actually execute jobs or interact with the OS.","test_description":"Parametrized unit tests with pairs of schedule objects at various temporal relationships: overlapping windows, exactly at minimum-gap boundary (critical boundary case), separated beyond gap, identical start times, one schedule nested inside another. Verify detector correctly identifies conflicts/non-conflicts and reports accurate conflicting time windows.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.95,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Timezone-aware scheduling produces correct run times across a DST transition — a job scheduled for 2:30 AM handles the spring-forward gap and fall-back ambiguity correctly.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"DST transitions are deterministic calendar rules, not non-deterministic external behavior. Testing correctness requires real timezone library objects (e.g., pytz, zoneinfo) rather than mocks, but does not require system-level interaction. The critical failures (treating spring-forward gap as a valid time, picking wrong occurrence in fall-back ambiguity, using naive datetime instead of timezone-aware) can be caught by unit tests using actual timezone definitions and verifying calculation logic around known DST transition moments. No OS environment changes or subprocess calls needed.","test_description":"Unit tests with real timezone objects (not mocked) for a timezone with known DST transitions (e.g., US/Eastern with 2024-03-10 spring-forward and 2024-11-03 fall-back). Schedule a job at 2:30 AM and compute next-run times across transition boundaries: verify spring-forward gap is skipped (2:30 AM does not exist, next run jumps to 3:30 AM EDT), and fall-back ambiguity resolves consistently (correct occurrence selected).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When a scheduled job's computed next run time has already passed (e.g., system was down), the engine determines whether to skip or backfill based on the job's configured missed-run policy.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Missed-run policy application is pure decision logic: given a job configuration (policy flag), a schedule, and a reference time in the past, determine whether to skip or backfill missed runs. No job execution, no actual delays, no external state. Real failures (wrong policy field read, off-by-one in backfill count, incorrect skip logic) can be caught entirely with unit tests varying policy flags and past reference times. No I/O or integration needed.","test_description":"Parametrized unit tests with job configurations covering both skip and backfill policies (skip_missed_runs=true/false, backfill_missed_runs=true/false), a reference time in the past relative to schedule start, and diverse schedule patterns (daily, weekly, hourly). Verify the scheduler applies the correct policy: skips the appropriate number of runs for skip policy, correctly computes backfill for backfill policy.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":27995,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":27995},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1a62c471-cfb8-42b5-afa4-2ed97c2b2a0f","uuid":"067d7e69-7a0d-43a4-b098-6e50e1f3fbe7"}
